<p class=3D"noindent">The value of this final estimate for the given exampl=
e is <em>y*(h)=3D2.0112</em>. This is quite close to the exact solution<em>=
 y(h)=3D3e<sup>-2(0.2)</sup>=3D2.0110</em>. <span class=3D"note">Note: As s=
tated previously, we generally won't know the exact solution as we do in th=
is case.</span></p>
<p>We can repeat this process using this estimate as our starting point to =
generate a solution over time.</p>
<div class=3D"example" id=3D"RK4Example">
  <h5 id=3D"#section10" class=3D"section-heading">Example 1: Approximation =
of First Order Differential Equation with No Input Using MATLAB</h5>
  <p> We can use MATLAB to perform the calculation described above.A simple=
 loop accomplishes this:  </p>
  <pre class=3D"Matlab">% Solve y'(t)=3D-2y(t) with y0=3D3, 4th order Runge=
 Kutta
y0 =3D 3;                  % Initial Condition
h=3D0.2;                   % Time step
t =3D 0:h:2;               % t goes from 0 to 2 seconds.
yexact =3D 3*exp(-2*t)     % Exact solution (in general we won't know this
ystar =3D zeros(size(t));  % Preallocate array (good coding practice)

ystar(1) =3D y0;           % Initial condition gives solution at t=3D0.
for i=3D1:(length(t)-1)
 =20
  k1 =3D -2*ystar(i)  % Approx for y gives approx for deriv
  y1 =3D ystar(i)+k1*h/2;      % Intermediate value (using k1)
 =20
  k2 =3D -2*y1        % Approx deriv at intermediate value.
  y2 =3D ystar(i)+k2*h/2;      % Intermediate value (using k2)
 =20
  k3 =3D -2*y2        % Another approx deriv at intermediate value.
  y3 =3D ystar(i)+k3*h;        % Endpoint value (using k3)
 =20
  k4 =3D -2*y3        % Approx deriv at endpoint value.
 =20
  ystar(i+1) =3D ystar(i) + (k1+2*k2+2*k3+k4)*h/6; % Approx soln
end
plot(t,yexact,t,ystar);
legend('Exact','Approximate');</pre>
  <p class=3D"noindent">The MATLAB commands match up easily with the steps =
of the algorithm. A slight variation of the code was used to show the effec=
t of the size of <em>h</em>on the accuracy of the solution (see image  belo=
w). Note that larger values of <em>h</em> result in poorer approximations, =
but that the solutions are much better than <a href=3D"https://lpsa.swarthm=
ore.edu/NumInt/NumIntSecond.html#Example1">those obtained with the Second O=
rder Runge-Kutta</a> for the same value of <em>h</em>. This isn't obvious f=
or small <em>h</em>, but is for the curve where <em>h=3D0.8</em>.</p>
